  <!-- S1 -->
  <div class="content-block" id="s1">
    <h2>1. Interviewer Profile — ML Engineer Turned Satellite Ops Lead</h2>

    <div class="profile-box">
      <h4>GAUTHIER DAMIEN — CAREER TRACE</h4>
      <p style="font-family:'Share Tech Mono',monospace;font-size:12px;line-height:1.8;color:#555;">
        GlobalEnglish → First ML Engineer → Built Automatic English Lesson Generator and Automatic English Pronunciation Scorer. First ML hire: designed the data pipeline, trained the models, shipped the product.<br><br>
        Feedly → ML Engineer → Developed AI research assistant. Worked on content classification, relevance ranking, NLP pipeline infrastructure in a production SaaS environment.<br><br>
        Loft Orbital → Lead, Mission Operation Services → Develops satellite operations software. Applies software engineering methodology to constellation management. Supports satellite commissioning and daily operations. Recently leading Loft's AI-for-Space initiative — thinking about autonomous agents at constellation scale.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>The frame that matters</h3>
    <p>Gauthier has written publicly about the intersection of large-scale autonomous AI systems and space infrastructure. He thinks about what happens when you network capable autonomous agents at scale — emergent coordination, shared context, second-order effects. He sees satellite operations as a domain ripe for this approach: instead of a team of humans operating each satellite manually, systems of software agents managing the fleet autonomously, with humans supervising at the policy level rather than the command level.</p>

    <p>This means his question is not "can you write Python?" — it's "do you think about automated systems the way a software engineer who has shipped production ML pipelines thinks about them?" Does your automation have error handling, retry logic, idempotency guarantees, monitoring hooks? Do you think about failure modes before you think about happy paths? Do you design for observability so that when something goes wrong at 2am you can see exactly what happened and why?</p>

    <h3>The opportunity this creates for you</h3>
    <p>Your LEOAF platform is directly relevant here. You didn't just write lessons — you designed and built a full-stack web application: GitHub Pages frontend, Supabase (PostgreSQL) backend, authentication, progress tracking, a curriculum state machine (quarters, lessons, completion states). That is exactly the kind of software thinking Gauthier respects. Use it. Not as "I have a side project" but as "I designed the data model, I implemented the auth flow, I debugged the async state management issues when the HAL modal wasn't triggering correctly." The specifics matter because they signal the mindset.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- S2 -->
  <div class="content-block" id="s2">
    <h2>2. SatDevOps: What Loft Means by It and Why It Matters</h2>

    <p>"SatDevOps" — satellite operations run like a software DevOps organisation — is not just a branding phrase at Loft. It represents a genuine architectural philosophy: the team that builds the operations software is the same team that runs the operations. This collapses the traditional gap between "the people who write the tools" and "the people who use the tools" that characterises legacy satellite operations.</p>

    <h3>Traditional satellite ops vs SatDevOps</h3>

    <table class="compare-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Traditional Satellite Ops</th><th>Loft SatDevOps Model</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Operations team runs procedures written by others</td><td>Operations team writes and owns the procedures as code</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tool requests go to a separate engineering team</td><td>Ops engineers build and deploy the tools they need</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Runbooks are Word documents updated annually</td><td>Runbooks are code — version-controlled, tested, automated</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Anomaly response is manual and operator-driven</td><td>Anomaly response is automated where safe, supervised where not</td></tr>
        <tr><td>One operator per mission, high workload</td><td>Software manages the fleet; humans supervise exceptions</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Scaling from 5 to 50 satellites requires 10× ops headcount</td><td>Scaling from 5 to 50 satellites requires better software, not 10× headcount</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>The business case for SatDevOps is constellation economics: as Loft scales from tens to hundreds of satellites, manual per-satellite operations don't scale linearly. Software that automates routine operations (health checks, pass scheduling, telemetry trend monitoring, nominal commanding sequences) allows the same operations team to manage a much larger fleet. CDEs in this model are not data-entry operators executing fixed procedures — they are software-aware engineers who can read, contribute to, and critically evaluate the automation layer.</p>

    <h3>What this means for you as a CDE candidate</h3>
    <p>Gauthier is evaluating whether you will be a consumer of the automation (running other people's tools passively) or a contributor (identifying gaps, writing small automation pieces, providing high-quality feedback that improves the system). Your automation background — Ansible at iDirect, Python scripting, the SNMP/REST integration work at Airbus HBC+ — demonstrates the contributor instinct. Frame it that way.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>THE KEY DISTINCTION TO MAKE IN THE INTERVIEW</strong>
      <p>There is a difference between running automated tools and having the engineering discipline that makes automated tools trustworthy. Anyone can schedule a cron job. The question is whether you write the cron job with idempotency so it can safely retry, with logging so you can reconstruct what happened, with error handling that distinguishes transient failures from hard failures, and with alerting that wakes the right person at the right severity. Gauthier cares about the second thing.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- S3 -->
  <div class="content-block" id="s3">
    <h2>3. Automation as System Design — Not Scripts, Systems</h2>

    <p>The most important conceptual distinction for this interview is between a script and a system. Scripts execute a task. Systems manage tasks over time, handle failures, maintain state, and provide visibility into what they're doing. Gauthier has built ML systems in production — he knows the difference viscerally.</p>

    <div class="concept-grid">
      <div class="concept-card">
        <h4>IDEMPOTENCY</h4>
        <p>Running the same operation N times produces the same result as running it once. Critical for satellite commanding: if a command is sent and you don't receive an ACK, can you safely resend? Only if the operation is idempotent (e.g. "set payload power to ON") vs non-idempotent (e.g. "toggle payload power").</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-card">
        <h4>RETRY LOGIC</h4>
        <p>Transient failures (network timeout, temporary API error) should be retried with exponential backoff + jitter. Permanent failures (4xx errors, invalid state) should not be retried — they require human intervention. Distinguishing the two is the difference between a resilient system and one that amplifies problems.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-card">
        <h4>OBSERVABILITY</h4>
        <p>A system is observable if its internal state can be inferred from its external outputs — logs, metrics, traces. Gauthier's ML background makes him especially attuned to this: a model that performs well in dev but fails silently in prod is the canonical observability failure. Same principle applies to ops automation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-card">
        <h4>GRACEFUL DEGRADATION</h4>
        <p>When one component fails, the system should degrade in a controlled way, not collapse entirely. Satellite ops automation that falls back to manual intervention on failure is better than automation that cascades a partial failure into a full outage. Design for degradation explicitly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-card">
        <h4>SEPARATION OF CONCERNS</h4>
        <p>A commanding module shouldn't also do telemetry parsing. A scheduler shouldn't also do anomaly detection. Clean separation makes each component independently testable, replaceable, and debuggable. In microservices terms: each service owns its domain and exposes a well-defined interface.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-card">
        <h4>HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP DESIGN</h4>
        <p>Autonomous systems should be designed with explicit points where human oversight is required — not bolted on as an afterthought. For satellite ops: automated nominal operations, human approval required for anything that changes the spacecraft's operating mode or power state significantly. Design the boundary explicitly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Applying this to a satellite operations context</h3>
    <p>Consider a daily health check automation: a script that polls each satellite's telemetry every 15 minutes and flags anomalies. As a script: it polls, prints results, exits. As a system: it maintains a state model of each satellite (what's normal for this satellite at this orbital position, this time of day, this mission phase), detects deviations from the state model rather than from fixed thresholds, logs every evaluation with structured output, emits alerts to the right channel at the right severity, tracks alert history to suppress duplicate notifications, and exposes a dashboard showing current fleet health at a glance. The system is dramatically more useful — and dramatically more complex to build correctly. Gauthier wants evidence that you think at the system level, not the script level.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- S4 -->
  <div class="content-block" id="s4">
    <h2>4. Observability: The Infrastructure of Trust</h2>

    <p>Observability is the property that allows you to understand a system's internal state from its external outputs without modifying the system to get that understanding. It is the answer to "what is happening right now, and why?" when something unexpected occurs. Gauthier, as someone who has debugged ML models in production, has strong opinions about observability.</p>

    <h3>The three pillars</h3>
    <p>Logs provide a chronological record of events. Good logs are structured (JSON, not free text), include context (satellite ID, mission phase, command reference), and are queryable. Bad logs are printf statements that tell you something happened but not what state the system was in when it happened. Metrics provide quantitative measurements over time — SoC trend, command success rate, data downlink volume per pass, API response latency. Traces connect a user action (a CDE sends a command via Cockpit) through the entire software stack (Cockpit API → ground station controller → uplink scheduler → RF transmission → command ACK receipt) to the outcome. For satellite ops, traces help diagnose "why did this command not reach the satellite" when the failure could be at any layer of the software stack.</p>

    <h3>Why this connects to your background</h3>
    <p>Your iDirect NMS experience is an observability system. iDirect's Network Management System provides exactly these three pillars for the VSAT network: event logs, time-series metrics (SNR, throughput, remotes online), and the ability to trace a connectivity failure from the remote terminal through the hub to the network. You've used it diagnostically every day for five years. You understand what good observability enables and what missing observability costs — in time, in customer impact, in the cognitive load of debugging without sufficient data.</p>

    <p>Your Airbus HBC+ work also connects: designing SNMP monitoring interfaces for the MSP onboarding is explicitly building the metrics layer for a distributed system. You defined what gets measured, at what granularity, and how it flows to the NMS. That is an observability design decision.</p>

    <div class="callout green">
      <strong>THE LEOAF OBSERVABILITY ANGLE</strong>
      <p>Your LEOAF platform has a Supabase backend tracking user progress — completion states, lesson IDs, timestamps. You designed a data model (what to store), an API layer (how the frontend reads and writes), and implicitly an observability layer (you can query Supabase to see how users progress through the curriculum, which lessons have the highest drop-off, how completion rates vary). That is a production observability decision, even if small-scale. Mentioning it to Gauthier as "I designed the data model with queryability in mind — not just to store state but to answer questions about how the system is used" will resonate strongly.</p>
    </div>
