  <div class="content-block" id="s5">
    <h2>5. State Machines and Mission Workflow Design</h2>

    <p>Satellite mission operations are fundamentally state machine problems. A satellite transitions between defined states (commissioning, nominal operations, payload active, payload idle, safe mode, end of life), and valid transitions between states are defined by operational rules and safety constraints. A CDE who understands state machines can design workflows that are safe, auditable, and automatable.</p>

    <h3>The satellite as a state machine</h3>
    <p>Consider the mission lifecycle as a state machine: LEOP → Commissioning → Nominal → Payload Active → (anomaly) → Safe Mode → (recovery) → Nominal. Each state has a set of valid transitions, guard conditions (conditions that must be true before a transition is allowed), and actions triggered by the transition. "Activate payload" is only a valid transition from Nominal, not from Safe Mode. "Safe mode" is always a valid transition from any state — it is the invariant recovery path.</p>

    <p>When you design automation for satellite operations, you are implementing this state machine in code. The commanding sequences are transitions. The telemetry checks before each command are guard conditions. The logging on transition is the audit trail. A CDE who can articulate this explicitly is demonstrating SatDevOps thinking — they understand that the ops workflow is a software artifact, not just a procedure document.</p>

    <h3>Workflow design principles for satellite ops</h3>
    <p>Atomic operations: each commanding step should be atomic — it either completes fully or it fails cleanly, never leaving the spacecraft in an intermediate state that's hard to reason about. Before proceeding to the next step, verify the previous step's success condition. Checkpoint and resume: for long commanding sequences (payload commissioning, firmware updates), design checkpoints where the current state is recorded and the sequence can be safely resumed from if interrupted by a contact loss. Roll-forward not rollback: on orbit, rolling back a state change is often impossible. Design commanding sequences where every intermediate state is safe, so that stopping at any point leaves the spacecraft in a known, manageable state.</p>

    <div class="callout amber">
      <strong>THE LEOAF CURRICULUM AS A STATE MACHINE</strong>
      <p>Your curriculum platform is itself a state machine: each lesson is a node, completion is a transition, quarters are aggregated states. The Supabase backend stores the state. The frontend renders the current state. User actions (clicking "Mark Complete") trigger transitions. The progress bars and completion indicators are state visualisations. If Gauthier asks about your experience with state management, you can describe LEOAF in exactly these terms — it is not just a "website," it is a state management system for a learner's progress through a 620-hour curriculum. Frame it with that precision.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

